  <!-- Key Concepts -->
  <div class="section-header" style="margin-top: 56px;">
    <div class="section-icon" style="background: var(--purple-dim); color: var(--purple);">
      <svg class="icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/></svg>
    </div>
    <h2>Key Concepts</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="about-grid">
    <div class="about-card">
      <h3>
        <svg class="icon" style="color: var(--accent);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><rect x="3" y="3" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/><rect x="14" y="3" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/><rect x="3" y="14" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/><rect x="14" y="14" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/></svg>
        Classic (V1) Tables
      </h3>
      <p>Custom log tables created via the legacy HTTP Data Collector API. Identified by the _CL suffix and Classic subtype. These are the tables that need migrating.</p>
      <a class="doc-link" href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/logs/custom-logs-migrate" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Migration guide &#8594;</a>
    </div>
    <div class="about-card">
      <h3>
        <svg class="icon" style="color: var(--ok);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"/></svg>
        DCR-Based Tables
      </h3>
      <p>The new table format using Data Collection Rules for ingestion. Supports the Logs Ingestion API, Data Lake mirroring, and clean column schemas.</p>
      <a class="doc-link" href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/essentials/data-collection-rule-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DCR overview &#8594;</a>
    </div>
    <div class="about-card">
      <h3>
        <svg class="icon" style="color: var(--err);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><polyline points="12 6 12 12 16 14"/></svg>
        API Retirement
      </h3>
      <p>The HTTP Data Collector API retires on <strong style="color:var(--err);">September 14, 2026</strong>. After this date, classic table ingestion stops entirely. All custom log tables must use the Logs Ingestion API via DCRs.</p>
      <a class="doc-link" href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/logs/custom-logs-migrate#why-migrate" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Retirement details &#8594;</a>
    </div>
    <div class="about-card">
      <h3>
        <svg class="icon" style="color: var(--warn);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M4 19.5A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 6.5 17H20"/><path d="M6.5 2H20v20H6.5A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 4 19.5v-15A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 6.5 2z"/></svg>
        Content Hub Solutions
      </h3>
      <p>Pre-built analytics rules, hunting queries, and workbooks from Microsoft and partners. Solutions are matched to your tables to ensure detection coverage after migration.</p>
      <a class="doc-link" href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/sentinel/sentinel-solutions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Content Hub &#8594;</a>
    </div>
    <div class="about-card">
      <h3>
        <svg class="icon" style="color: var(--cyan);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 3h12l4 6-10 13L2 9z"/></svg>
        Data Lake Compatibility
      </h3>
      <p>Classic tables cannot be mirrored to the Microsoft Sentinel Data Lake tier. Migrating to DCR-based tables unlocks unified long-term storage and cross-workspace queries.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="about-card">
      <h3>
        <svg class="icon" style="color: var(--purple);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><line x1="6" y1="3" x2="6" y2="15"/><circle cx="18" cy="6" r="3"/><circle cx="6" cy="18" r="3"/><path d="M18 9a9 9 0 0 1-9 9"/></svg>
        Schema Consistency
      </h3>
      <p>Classic columns use auto-inferred type suffixes (_s, _d, _b, _g, _t) that break KQL in analytics rules, workbooks, and playbooks. DCR-based tables use clean, predictable column names.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

